---
import { Image } from "astro:assets";
import Presentation from "../../../components/Presentation.astro";
import Divider from "../../../components/ui/Divider.astro";
import Layout from "../../../layouts/Layout.astro";
import { Code as CodeSnippet } from "astro:components";

import IoModelDiagram from "../../../assets/courses/ap-csp/img/io-model-diagram.svg";
import BinaryByteDiagram from "../../../assets/courses/ap-csp/img/binary-byte-diagram.svg";
---

<Layout>
  <div class="container my-4">
    <div class="row justify-content-center">
      <div class="col-sm-12 col-md-10">
        <a href="/courses/ap-csp/" class="btn btn-sm btn-outline-light mb-3">
          <i class="si-arrow-left"></i> Back
        </a>

        <h1>Activity 1.1: Computer Systems</h1>
        <Divider variant="8" classes="mb-5" />

        <!-- Launch / Concept -->
        <section id="launch">
          <Presentation>
            <section>
              <h2>Activity 1.1</h2>
              <h3 class="text-sn-theme">Computer Systems</h3>
            </section>

            <section>
              <h2>Key Concepts</h2>
              <p>How a Computer Works</p>
              <p>Input, Processing, Output, and Memory</p>
              <p>Binary</p>
            </section>

            <section data-auto-animate>
              <h2>The Four Basic Functions</h2>
              <p>
                Every computer, from a laptop to a microwave, performs the
                same four basic functions.
              </p>
            </section>

            <section data-auto-animate>
              <h2>The Four Basic Functions</h2>
              <Image src={IoModelDiagram} alt="Diagram showing Input flowing into Processing (CPU), Processing flowing into Output, and Memory connected to Processing" width={640} />
            </section>

            <section data-auto-animate data-auto-animate-restart>
              <h2>Input</h2>
              <p>Information a computer receives from the outside world.</p>
              <ul>
                <li class="fragment">Keyboard and mouse</li>
                <li class="fragment">Microphone and camera</li>
                <li class="fragment">Sensors (temperature, motion, light)</li>
              </ul>
            </section>

            <section data-auto-animate data-auto-animate-restart>
              <h2>Output</h2>
              <p>Information a computer sends back out to the world.</p>
              <ul>
                <li class="fragment">Monitor and speakers</li>
                <li class="fragment">Printer</li>
                <li class="fragment">LEDs and motors</li>
              </ul>
            </section>

            <section data-auto-animate data-auto-animate-restart>
              <h2>Processing</h2>
              <p>
                The <b class="text-sn-theme">CPU</b> (Central Processing Unit)
                is the "brain" of the computer. It carries out instructions
                and makes decisions, one step at a time.
              </p>
            </section>

            <section data-auto-animate data-auto-animate-restart>
              <h2>Memory</h2>
              <p>
                Computers need somewhere to hold data while they work, and
                somewhere to keep it long-term.
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li class="fragment">
                  <b>RAM</b> &mdash; temporary, cleared when the power turns
                  off
                </li>
                <li class="fragment">
                  <b>Storage</b> (like a hard drive or SSD) &mdash; permanent,
                  kept even after the power turns off
                </li>
              </ul>
            </section>

            <section data-auto-animate data-auto-animate-restart>
              <h2>Binary</h2>
              <p>
                Underneath everything a computer does, it only understands two
                states: <b class="text-sn-theme">on</b> and <b class="text-sn-theme">off</b>.
              </p>
              <p class="fragment">
                We represent those two states as <CodeSnippet
                  code="1"
                  lang={"javascript"}
                  theme={"material-theme-ocean"}
                  inline
                /> and <CodeSnippet
                  code="0"
                  lang={"javascript"}
                  theme={"material-theme-ocean"}
                  inline
                />. Each one is called a <b>bit</b>.
              </p>
            </section>

            <section data-auto-animate>
              <h2>Binary</h2>
              <Image src={BinaryByteDiagram} alt="Diagram showing eight bits, 01000001, grouped together as one byte representing the letter A" width={620} />
              <p class="fragment">
                Eight bits grouped together make one <b>byte</b>.
              </p>
            </section>

            <section>
              <h2>Today's Objectives</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>Identifying input, processing, output, and memory</li>
                <li>Understanding binary as a computer's "language"</li>
              </ul>
            </section>

            <section>
              <h2>Key Terms</h2>
              <div class="text-start">
                <dl>
                  <dt>Input</dt>
                  <dd>Information a computer receives from the outside world.</dd>
                  <dt>Output</dt>
                  <dd>Information a computer sends back out to the world.</dd>
                  <dt>Processing (CPU)</dt>
                  <dd>The part of the computer that carries out instructions.</dd>
                  <dt>Memory</dt>
                  <dd>Where a computer holds data, either temporarily (RAM) or long-term (storage).</dd>
                  <dt>Binary</dt>
                  <dd>A system of representing information using only two states, on and off.</dd>
                  <dt>Bit</dt>
                  <dd>A single binary digit, either 0 or 1.</dd>
                  <dt>Byte</dt>
                  <dd>A group of eight bits.</dd>
                </dl>
              </div>
            </section>
          </Presentation>
        </section>

        <Divider variant="8" classes="my-5" />

        <!-- Build -->
        <section id="build">
          <h2>Build</h2>

          <p>No coding yet &mdash; today is about recognizing these ideas in the devices you already use.</p>

          <hr class="my-4" />

          <h3>Task 1: Find the Four Functions in a Real Device</h3>
          <ul>
            <li>Pick a device you use every day (phone, laptop, game console, car, microwave).</li>
            <li>List at least one real example of that device's input, output, processing, and memory.</li>
          </ul>

          <hr class="my-4" />

          <h3>Task 2: Spot the Bits</h3>
          <ul>
            <li>
              Look at the byte diagram from the presentation
              (<CodeSnippet code="01000001" lang="txt" theme="material-theme-ocean" inline />).
            </li>
            <li>Count how many total on/off combinations are possible in one byte, and write down how you figured it out.</li>
          </ul>
        </section>

        <Divider variant="8" classes="my-5" />

        <!-- Checkpoint -->
        <section id="checkpoint">
          <h2>Checkpoint</h2>

          <p>You should be able to explain, in your own words:</p>
          <ul>
            <li>One real example each of input, processing, output, and memory from your chosen device.</li>
            <li>Why a byte can represent 256 different values.</li>
          </ul>
        </section>

        <Divider variant="8" classes="my-5" />

        <!-- Reflection -->
        <section id="reflection">
          <h2>Reflection</h2>

          <p>Answer the following questions before submitting your work.</p>

          <ol>
            <li>
              Which of the four basic functions (input, processing, output,
              memory) do you think is most similar to a human's brain?
              Explain your reasoning.
            </li>
            <li>
              Why do you think computers only use binary (0s and 1s) instead
              of the decimal numbers people use every day?
            </li>
            <li>
              Pick one device from Task 1 that surprised you once you broke
              it down into input/processing/output/memory. What surprised
              you about it?
            </li>
          </ol>
        </section>

        <Divider variant="8" classes="my-5" />

        <!-- Submit -->
        <section id="submit">
          <h2>Submit</h2>

          <p>Submit the required files to the appropriate dropbox.</p>

          <h1
            class="text-center mt-5 text-sn-theme border border-primary slow-flash"
          >
            Activity Complete
          </h1>
        </section>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</Layout>
